Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30 a.m., Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially since it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently getting out of his cot, he put on his combat uniform, strapped on his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks, the sound of squelching mud and crunching ice echoing under his boots.
He took out a lighter from the pocket of his tactical vest and a cigarette from the other side. Lighting it, he took a small puff before opening the door gently. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm, which half the time didn't work, as the sound coming from the speakers was just a faint whistle.
"Are you waking them up?" Cohren turned to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching.
"Yep," replied Cohren.
"What are you planning to use this time?"
Before he could reply, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" asked Cohren.
"Well, first of all, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Second, the first shock troops up are the first to breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how terrible it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He reached out and activated a switch. A loud, shrill alarm sounded inside the barracks. He heard commotion and chatter inside.
"Damnit, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they would have learned to wake up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here did it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But again, their squad and section leaders know how to wake up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company poured out en masse. Everyone had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, while others looked more irritated.
"Good morning everyone," said Cohren cheerfully.
"Sir, may I ask why you insist on waking us up this way?" asked one of the shock troop squad members, a corporal.
"Because the standard alarms are shit. And because Daybreak doesn't hit the sack late," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal effects," he continued. As first lieutenant and assistant to the commander, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to conduct final checks and retrieve rations for the day."
The members of Company Exodus dispersed. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, second army. Initially, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. This was a splinter company, and Cohren wasn't sure how to feel about his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly due to the reasons that motivated it.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked together under the light of the many forward operating base illuminations, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to conceal them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel assaults, both in the air and on the ground, to combat them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," Nemic began with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"A forward operating base outside Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground assault," replied Cohren, drawing on his cigarette. A part of him blamed Craith for having introduced him to smoking, but a year of combat changes a man, and he fell silent.
"Shit. The situation is worsening on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming from there is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send aid to the Kurgan front.' Why not send aid to the Howland front?"
"Amen, my brother," said Cohren, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're leaving with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to march. Captain Shaw should be here."
"Shaw got us a transport?" asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Yeah. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren placed his thumb and index finger on his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "All Exodus company units, assemble at the west vehicle park once you're done. We leave with the first armored platoon at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squadron commanders. Harris, Craith, and Ravik had all been junior NCOs when they arrived here. The four of them had been very good friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like such a long time ago, even though it couldn't be more than two years. They had then been squadron commanders. But Craith now commanded the second platoon since last week, after the demobilization of the previous commander, injured by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked toward the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main Kronos battle tanks and four Strykers. Their crews were busy, making sure their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the armored platoon commander. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked toward them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
